  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "cf092dee",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Model Selection Reasoning\n",
    "\n",
    "### We settle on a **Random Forest Regressor** for our model. We chose it over linear regression because the relationship between a song’s audio features (like danceability, energy, tempo, and loudness) and its popularity is highly nonlinear and involves complex interactions that a simple linear model cannot capture well. Linear regression assumes a straight-line relationship and independence between features, which is unrealistic for music data where combinations of features (e.g., high energy and high danceability) can jointly influence popularity. In contrast, Random Forest builds an ensemble of decision trees that can model these nonlinear patterns and feature interactions without requiring strong assumptions about the data. It is also more robust to outliers, handles skewed feature distributions naturally, and reduces overfitting through averaging across many trees, making it a better fit for predicting a noisy, real-world outcome like song popularity."
   ]
  },
